[2
From: "Grabenstein, John D LTC OTSG"
<John.Grabenstein@otsg.amedd.army.mil>
Subject: Gulf war syndrome - antibodies to squalene
Date: Fri 11 Feb 2000
In Drs. Asa, Cao, and Garry's article in Experimental & Molecular
Pathology, I certainly did see the mention of positive controls and
negative controls. My concern is about the scientific adequacy of the
controls selected. I tried to convey that the controls were not "proper."
Given that squalene is already in every human body, I'm concerned that we
don't know from the paper if the positive controls already had antibodies
before receiving the NIH
placebo. Nor do we know as an explicit experiment that intentional
injection of squalene will lead to antibodies to a substance already
present. Similarly, for negative controls: if the NIH product is believed
to induce anti-squalene antibodies, are there data to show that the test is
negative before the injection of the squalene-containing placebo? The standard
scientific approach is to change just one variable at a time, not to change
both the sample (the group of humans studied) and the exposure (NIH's
squalene-containing product) simultaneously.
It is a fine scientific goal to search for an assay that would reliably
detect anti-squalene antibodies. Once we have one, it will be useful in a
variety of research and clinical settings, including assessing the health
of Persian Gulf War veterans. But if we aren't certain what a test is
measuring, it's premature to proceed.
The healthy give-and-take of scientific discourse is intended to result in
ever-better science. If I am wrong, that will become apparent in due
course. Peer reviewers have certainly taught me many things and pointed out
my shortcomings often enough in my career.
--
LTC John D. Grabenstein, RPh, PhD, Medical Service Corps
Deputy Director for Clinical Operations
Anthrax Vaccine Immunization Program (AVIP) Agency
U.S. Army Medical Command
5111 Leesburg Pike (Suite 401)
Falls Church, VA 22041-3258
